Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER STATE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parallel-list lexer state: tokens, lexemes, and source lines are three
arrays of equal length whose ith element together describes one
emitted token. Keeping them parallel (rather than packing into a tagged
struct per token) lets each list type stay primitive (Integer or
String) without allocating one record per token. current_char is
cached as a String single-character lookahead so character classifiers
don't need to re-index source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Eight fields:
- source - the input text being scanned
- position - byte offset into source (advances monotonically)
- line, column - 1-based source coordinates updated by advance and
  handle_newline
- current_char - empty string at EOF, otherwise the single character at
  source[position..position+1]
- tokens - parallel Integer list of TOKEN_* type tags
- lexemes - parallel String list of token text
- lines - parallel Integer list of source line each token started on
@End Implementation
Type called "ElixirLexer":
    source as String
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    current_char as String
    tokens as List[Integer]
    lexemes as List[String]
    lines as List[Integer]
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructor establishing the parallel-list invariant (three empty
lists) and priming current_char so the first character is available
to the dispatcher without an extra advance call. Source-empty case is
handled by leaving current_char as "", which causes the main lex loop
to terminate immediately.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an ElixirLexer value with: source = source, position = 0,
line = 1, column = 1, current_char = "", three empty lists. If length
of source > 0, sets current_char to source[0..1] so the first
character is loaded. Returns the lexer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_lexer" that takes source as String returns ElixirLexer:
    Let lexer be a value of type ElixirLexer with
        source as source,
        position as 0,
        line as 1,
        column as 1,
        current_char as "",
        tokens as a list containing nothing,
        lexemes as a list containing nothing,
        lines as a list containing nothing

    Note: Initialize first character
    If length of source is greater than 0:
        Set lexer.current_char to substring of source from 0 to 1
    End If

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER NAVIGATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single character-consumption step. Updates position, column, and the
cached current_char lookahead atomically so any code path that reads
current_char after a call to advance sees the new character without
needing a separate refresh step. EOF is signalled by current_char ""
rather than a position check so classifiers can ask "is this still
text?" with one string comparison.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Increments position by 1. If the new position is still within source,
loads source[position..position+1] into current_char and increments
column. Otherwise (past EOF) sets current_char to "" - column is
deliberately not advanced so the reported column at EOF matches the
column of the last real character. Note: handle_newline is the only
path that resets column to 1; advance itself never touches the line
field.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Set lexer.position to lexer.position plus 1

    If lexer.position is less than length of lexer.source:
        Set lexer.current_char to substring of lexer.source from lexer.position to lexer.position plus 1
        Set lexer.column to lexer.column plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set lexer.current_char to ""
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bounded multi-character lookahead used by operator and triple-quote
heredoc detection. Returns "" past EOF rather than throwing so the
caller can compare against any expected character without first
asking how many characters are left.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes pos = position + offset. If pos < length of source, returns
the single character at source[pos..pos+1]. Otherwise returns "" so
EOF lookahead yields a comparison-safe sentinel.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer, offset as Integer returns String:
    Let pos be lexer.position plus offset

    If pos is less than length of lexer.source:
        Return substring of lexer.source from pos to pos plus 1
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralizes the parallel-list append invariant: tokens, lexemes, and
lines must always be the same length, so all three lists are extended
in a single procedure. Any code path that wants to emit a token must
go through here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Appends token_type to lexer.tokens, lexeme to lexer.lexemes, and the
current lexer.line to lexer.lines (so the source-line field reflects
the line on which the lexer was sitting when the token was emitted).
@End Implementation
Process called "add_token" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer, token_type as Integer, lexeme as String returns Nothing:
    Add token_type to end of lexer.tokens
    Add lexeme to end of lexer.lexemes
    Add lexer.line to end of lexer.lines
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Excludes newline from the "whitespace" set so the dispatcher can call
handle_newline separately and bump the line counter; bundling \n into
this predicate would lose source position tracking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true if char is space, tab, or carriage return. Carriage return
is included so CRLF line endings have their CR consumed as whitespace
while the LF is still handled by the dedicated newline path.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If char is equal to " " or char is equal to tab or char is equal to carriage_return:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-character newline predicate kept separate from is_whitespace so
the main loop can choose between handle_newline (which advances
lexer.line) and skip_whitespace (which doesn't).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns char == newline.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_newline" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    Return char is equal to newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Decimal digit predicate used by lex_number and inside the float
decimal-point / exponent paths. Bounded ASCII comparison rather than a
unicode digit category because Elixir number literals only accept
ASCII 0-9.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true iff char lies in the inclusive range ['0', '9'].
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If char is greater than or equal to "0" and char is less than or equal to "9":
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognizes any of the 22 hex digit characters (0-9, a-f, A-F) for use
inside 0x... integer literals and \xNN string escape sequences.
Implemented as digit-first short-circuit because decimal digits are
the most common case in real source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true if is_digit(char), or char in [a..f], or char in [A..F].
Otherwise returns false. Each range is a single inclusive comparison.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_hex_digit" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If is_digit with char:
        Return true
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to "a" and char is less than or equal to "f":
        Return true
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to "A" and char is less than or equal to "F":
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII-letter predicate. Elixir identifiers are restricted to ASCII
letters plus `_` (and digits in non-start positions), so unicode
letters are intentionally rejected here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true if char in [a..z] or in [A..Z]; otherwise false.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If char is greater than or equal to "a" and char is less than or equal to "z":
        Return true
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to "A" and char is less than or equal to "Z":
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start in Elixir is letter or underscore. Digits are
forbidden in the first position to keep the lexer from misclassifying
`123abc` as a single identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true if is_alpha(char) or char == "_"; otherwise false.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_identifier_start" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If is_alpha with char:
        Return true
    End If

    If char is equal to "_":
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-continuation in Elixir extends is_identifier_start with
digits plus the special trailing `?` and `!` characters that mark
predicates and bang-functions. These trailing characters are only
valid as the final character of an identifier but the lexer accepts
any position - the parser will reject misplaced ones.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true if is_identifier_start(char), is_digit(char), or char is
"?" or "!". Otherwise false.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_identifier_char" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If is_identifier_start with char:
        Return true
    End If

    If is_digit with char:
        Return true
    End If

    If char is equal to "?" or char is equal to "!":
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Used by lex_identifier to distinguish a module name (starts with
uppercase) from a regular identifier or variable. Elixir module names
are syntactically uppercased - the kind of token emitted depends on
this single test.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true iff char in [A..Z]; otherwise false.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_uppercase" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    If char is greater than or equal to "A" and char is less than or equal to "Z":
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WHITESPACE AND COMMENTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Tight horizontal-whitespace skipper used between tokens. Doesn't emit
anything and doesn't cross newlines (those are handled by
handle_newline so line tracking stays accurate).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
While is_whitespace(current_char), call advance. Falls through when a
non-whitespace, EOF, or newline character is current.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    While is_whitespace with lexer.current_char:
        Call advance with lexer
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Elixir uses `#` for single-line comments. The lexer never emits a
comment token; it just consumes characters until the next newline (or
EOF) so the parser sees a clean token stream. handle_newline is called
afterwards by the main loop to advance the line counter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
While current_char is neither a newline nor "" (EOF), call advance.
The terminating newline itself is left for handle_newline so the line
counter increments correctly.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_comment" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Note: Skip # comment to end of line
    While not is_newline with lexer.current_char and lexer.current_char is not equal to "":
        Call advance with lexer
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Newlines are syntactically meaningful in Elixir (they can terminate
statements without an explicit ;), so they are emitted as
TOKEN_NEWLINE rather than skipped like horizontal whitespace. This
also lets the parser distinguish `a\nb` (two statements) from `a b`
(one call).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Adds a TOKEN_NEWLINE token with lexeme "\n", calls advance to consume
the newline character, increments lexer.line, and resets
lexer.column to 1 so the next non-newline token reports the correct
column position.
@End Implementation
Process called "handle_newline" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_NEWLINE, "\\n"
    Call advance with lexer
    Set lexer.line to lexer.line plus 1
    Set lexer.column to 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMBER LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Elixir number literals span five textual shapes: binary (0b...),
octal (0o...), hex (0x...), decimal integer, and float with optional
exponent. The `_` digit separator is accepted in every shape for
readability. The decimal-point lookahead requires the character after
`.` to be a digit so range syntax `1..10` isn't accidentally tokenized
as the float `1.` followed by `.10`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos, is_float=false. If current is "0", peeks for b/B,
o/O, or x/X; if matched, advances past the prefix and consumes
digits-of-that-radix or "_" until a non-matching character. Each
prefix branch emits TOKEN_INTEGER with the source-slice lexeme and
returns. Falls through to decimal: consume digits-or-underscore. If
current is "." and peek(1) is a digit, set is_float=true, advance past
".", consume digits-or-underscore again. If current is "e"/"E", set
is_float=true, advance, accept optional "+"/"-", consume digits-or-
underscore. Emits TOKEN_FLOAT or TOKEN_INTEGER based on is_float using
the substring from start_pos to current position.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_number" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position
    Let is_float be false

    Note: Check for binary, octal, hex notation
    If lexer.current_char is equal to "0":
        Let next_char be peek with lexer and 1

        If next_char is equal to "b" or next_char is equal to "B":
            Note: Binary number 0b1010
            Call advance with lexer
            Call advance with lexer

            While lexer.current_char is equal to "0" or lexer.current_char is equal to "1" or lexer.current_char is equal to "_":
                Call advance with lexer
            End While

            Let lexeme be substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
            Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER, lexeme
            Return

        Otherwise If next_char is equal to "o" or next_char is equal to "O":
            Note: Octal number 0o755
            Call advance with lexer
            Call advance with lexer

            While lexer.current_char is greater than or equal to "0" and lexer.current_char is less than or equal to "7" or lexer.current_char is equal to "_":
                Call advance with lexer
            End While

            Set lexeme to substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
            Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER, lexeme
            Return

        Otherwise If next_char is equal to "x" or next_char is equal to "X":
            Note: Hexadecimal number 0xFF
            Call advance with lexer
            Call advance with lexer

            While is_hex_digit with lexer.current_char or lexer.current_char is equal to "_":
                Call advance with lexer
            End While

            Set lexeme to substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
            Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER, lexeme
            Return
        End If
    End If

    Note: Regular integer or float
    While is_digit with lexer.current_char or lexer.current_char is equal to "_":
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    Note: Check for decimal point
    If lexer.current_char is equal to "." and is_digit with peek with lexer and 1:
        Set is_float to true
        Call advance with lexer

        While is_digit with lexer.current_char or lexer.current_char is equal to "_":
            Call advance with lexer
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check for exponent
    If lexer.current_char is equal to "e" or lexer.current_char is equal to "E":
        Set is_float to true
        Call advance with lexer

        If lexer.current_char is equal to "+" or lexer.current_char is equal to "-":
            Call advance with lexer
        End If

        While is_digit with lexer.current_char or lexer.current_char is equal to "_":
            Call advance with lexer
        End While
    End If

    Set lexeme to substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position

    If is_float:
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_FLOAT, lexeme
    Otherwise:
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER, lexeme
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRING LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Handles both `"..."` (string) and `'...'` (charlist) - the quote
character determines the token type. Detects triple-quoted heredocs
upfront and delegates to lex_heredoc rather than mixing the two
parsing modes in one loop. Escape sequences are decoded inline so the
emitted lexeme is the cooked value, not the raw source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos and the opening quote_char, advances past it. If the
next two characters also equal quote_char, calls lex_heredoc(lexer,
quote_char) and returns. Otherwise builds value = "" by looping:
- on "\\", advances and matches one of n, t, r, "\\", quote_char (each
  appends the corresponding character to value and advances), "x"
  (reads two hex digits, hex_to_int -> int_to_char), "u" (reads 4 hex
  digits via is_hex_digit loop, then hex_string_to_int and
  unicode_to_char). Unknown escapes pass through verbatim.
- on a newline (no heredoc), break - multiline strings without
  triple-quote syntax are rejected.
- otherwise append current and advance.
Closes by advancing past the closing quote if present. Emits
TOKEN_STRING for "..." and TOKEN_CHARLIST for '...'.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Escape decoding runs against untrusted source. Hex and unicode escapes
read fixed counts of characters; an out-of-range or non-hex character
inside a \u escape produces a reported error via report_lexer_error
rather than crashing or producing a wrong codepoint.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "lex_string" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position
    Let quote_char be lexer.current_char
    Call advance with lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    Note: Check for heredoc (triple quotes)
    If lexer.current_char is equal to quote_char and peek with lexer and 1 is equal to quote_char:
        Call lex_heredoc with lexer and quote_char
        Return
    End If

    Let value be ""

    While lexer.current_char is not equal to quote_char and lexer.current_char is not equal to "":
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "\\":
            Note: Escape sequence
            Call advance with lexer

            If lexer.current_char is equal to "n":
                Set value to value joined with newline
                Call advance with lexer
            Otherwise If lexer.current_char is equal to "t":
                Set value to value joined with tab
                Call advance with lexer
            Otherwise If lexer.current_char is equal to "r":
                Set value to value joined with carriage_return
                Call advance with lexer
            Otherwise If lexer.current_char is equal to "\\":
                Set value to value joined with "\\"
                Call advance with lexer
            Otherwise If lexer.current_char is equal to quote_char:
                Set value to value joined with quote_char
                Call advance with lexer
            Otherwise If lexer.current_char is equal to "x":
                Note: Hex escape \xNN
                Call advance with lexer
                Let hex1 be lexer.current_char
                Call advance with lexer
                Let hex2 be lexer.current_char
                Call advance with lexer
                Note: Convert hex digits to character
                Let hex_value be proc hex_to_int with hex1, hex2
                Let char_value be proc int_to_char from hex_value
                Set value to value joined with char_value
            Otherwise If lexer.current_char is equal to "u":
                Note: Unicode escape \uNNNN
                Call advance with lexer
                Note: Parse unicode digits \uNNNN
                Let unicode_hex be ""
                For i from 0 to 3:
                    If proc is_hex_digit with lexer.current_char is equal to 1:
                        Set unicode_hex to unicode_hex joined with lexer.current_char
                        Call advance with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Invalid unicode escape
                        Call report_lexer_error with lexer, "Invalid unicode escape sequence"
                        Break
                    End If
                End For
                Let unicode_value be proc hex_string_to_int from unicode_hex
                Let unicode_char be proc unicode_to_char from unicode_value
                Set value to value joined with unicode_char
            Otherwise:
                Set value to value joined with lexer.current_char
                Call advance with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise If is_newline with lexer.current_char:
            Note: Multiline strings not allowed without heredoc
            Break
        Otherwise:
            Set value to value joined with lexer.current_char
            Call advance with lexer
        End If
    End While

    If lexer.current_char is equal to quote_char:
        Call advance with lexer  Note: Skip closing quote
    End If

    If quote_char is equal to "\"":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING, value
    Otherwise:
        Note: Single quotes create charlists
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_CHARLIST, value
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Heredoc strings (`"""..."""` or `'''...'''`) preserve embedded
newlines and end only on a matching triple-quote sequence, so the
inner loop tracks newlines to maintain line counting while consuming
literal text without escape interpretation (escape handling differs
from normal strings; here we keep characters verbatim).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances three times to skip the opening triple-quote. value = "".
Loops:
- if current == quote_char and peek(1) == quote_char and peek(2) ==
  quote_char, advances three times to consume the closing triple-quote
  and breaks.
- if current is "" (EOF), breaks.
- if current is a newline, appends newline to value, advances,
  increments lexer.line, resets column to 1.
- otherwise appends current to value and advances.
Emits TOKEN_HEREDOC with the accumulated value (always treated as a
string-like token regardless of which quote character was used).
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_heredoc" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer, quote_char as String returns Nothing:
    Note: Skip three quotes
    Call advance with lexer
    Call advance with lexer
    Call advance with lexer

    Let value be ""

    While true:
        If lexer.current_char is equal to quote_char:
            If peek with lexer and 1 is equal to quote_char and peek with lexer and 2 is equal to quote_char:
                Note: Found closing triple quotes
                Call advance with lexer
                Call advance with lexer
                Call advance with lexer
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If lexer.current_char is equal to "":
            Break
        End If

        If is_newline with lexer.current_char:
            Set value to value joined with newline
            Call advance with lexer
            Set lexer.line to lexer.line plus 1
            Set lexer.column to 1
        Otherwise:
            Set value to value joined with lexer.current_char
            Call advance with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_HEREDOC, value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ATOM LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Elixir atoms come in two shapes: `:identifier` and `:"any quoted
content"`. The colon is required to be immediately followed by either
a quote (for the quoted form) or an identifier character. The lexer
keeps the leading colon as part of the lexeme so downstream consumers
can distinguish atoms from identifiers by inspecting the lexeme.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos (before the colon), advances past the colon. If the
next char is `"`, delegates to lex_quoted_atom and returns. Otherwise
consumes is_identifier_char characters until a non-matching one.
Emits TOKEN_ATOM with the substring from start_pos including the
colon.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_atom" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position
    Call advance with lexer  Note: Skip :

    Note: Check for quoted atom :\"atom name\"
    If lexer.current_char is equal to "\"":
        Call lex_quoted_atom with lexer
        Return
    End If

    Note: Regular atom
    While is_identifier_char with lexer.current_char:
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    Let lexeme be substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_ATOM, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Quoted atoms `:"..."` allow arbitrary content (including spaces and
operators) as the atom name. The lexer keeps the entire form
including colon and quotes in the lexeme so the printer can
round-trip without guessing. Escape sequences inside are accepted by
consuming the backslash plus the next character without interpreting
either - the parser handles cooking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
start_pos = position - 1 to include the already-consumed colon.
Advances past the opening quote. Loops while current is neither `"`
nor "": if current is `\\`, advances once extra to consume the
escaped character along with the backslash. Each iteration ends with
an advance. Advances past the closing `"` if present. Emits
TOKEN_ATOM with the substring from start_pos.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_quoted_atom" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position minus 1  Note: Include :
    Call advance with lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    While lexer.current_char is not equal to "\"" and lexer.current_char is not equal to "":
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "\\":
            Call advance with lexer
        End If
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    If lexer.current_char is equal to "\"":
        Call advance with lexer
    End If

    Let lexeme be substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_ATOM, lexeme
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IDENTIFIER AND KEYWORD LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifiers in Elixir resolve into three distinct token categories at
lex time: reserved keyword (when a get_keyword_type match exists),
module name (when the leading character is uppercase), or plain
identifier/variable. Doing the classification here keeps the parser
free of keyword-table lookups.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos and captures is_module = is_uppercase(current_char)
before consuming. Consumes is_identifier_char characters into a
substring lexeme. Calls get_keyword_type; if non-zero, emits with
that token type. Otherwise, if is_module is true emits
TOKEN_MODULE_NAME, else TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. Module-name detection uses
the pre-loop snapshot of the first character so trailing `?`/`!`
don't affect the classification.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_identifier" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position
    Let is_module be is_uppercase with lexer.current_char

    While is_identifier_char with lexer.current_char:
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    Let lexeme be substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position

    Note: Check for keyword
    Let token_type be get_keyword_type with lexeme

    If token_type is not equal to 0:
        Call add_token with lexer, token_type, lexeme
        Return
    End If

    Note: Module name (starts with uppercase) vs identifier/variable
    If is_module:
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_MODULE_NAME, lexeme
    Otherwise:
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, lexeme
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Linear-search keyword table. Encoded as a sequence of equality checks
(rather than a hash) for two reasons: it's self-documenting against
the Elixir spec, and the table is short enough (~40 keywords) that
the linear scan cost is dominated by the surrounding String creation
in the lexer. Returns 0 for non-keywords so the caller can fall
through to identifier classification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
String-equality cascade against every Elixir reserved word group:
- definition keywords: def, defp, defmodule, defmacro, defmacrop,
  defstruct, defprotocol, defimpl, defdelegate, defexception
- block keywords: do, end
- control flow: if, unless, cond, case, with, receive
- exception flow: try, rescue, catch, after, else, raise, throw
- expression keywords: when, fn, in, not, and, or, true, false, nil,
  for, quote, unquote, use, import, require, alias
Returns the corresponding TOKEN_* constant or 0 when no match.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_keyword_type" that takes word as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check all Elixir keywords
    If word is equal to "def":
        Return TOKEN_DEF
    End If

    If word is equal to "defp":
        Return TOKEN_DEFP
    End If

    If word is equal to "defmodule":
        Return TOKEN_DEFMODULE
    End If

    If word is equal to "defmacro":
        Return TOKEN_DEFMACRO
    End If

    If word is equal to "defmacrop":
        Return TOKEN_DEFMACROP
    End If

    If word is equal to "defstruct":
        Return TOKEN_DEFSTRUCT
    End If

    If word is equal to "defprotocol":
        Return TOKEN_DEFPROTOCOL
    End If

    If word is equal to "defimpl":
        Return TOKEN_DEFIMPL
    End If

    If word is equal to "defdelegate":
        Return TOKEN_DEFDELEGATE
    End If

    If word is equal to "defexception":
        Return TOKEN_DEFEXCEPTION
    End If

    If word is equal to "do":
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If

    If word is equal to "end":
        Return TOKEN_END
    End If

    If word is equal to "if":
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If

    If word is equal to "unless":
        Return TOKEN_UNLESS
    End If

    If word is equal to "cond":
        Return TOKEN_COND
    End If

    If word is equal to "case":
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If

    If word is equal to "with":
        Return TOKEN_WITH
    End If

    If word is equal to "receive":
        Return TOKEN_RECEIVE
    End If

    If word is equal to "try":
        Return TOKEN_TRY
    End If

    If word is equal to "rescue":
        Return TOKEN_RESCUE
    End If

    If word is equal to "catch":
        Return TOKEN_CATCH
    End If

    If word is equal to "after":
        Return TOKEN_AFTER
    End If

    If word is equal to "else":
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If

    If word is equal to "fn":
        Return TOKEN_FN
    End If

    If word is equal to "when":
        Return TOKEN_WHEN
    End If

    If word is equal to "and":
        Return TOKEN_AND
    End If

    If word is equal to "or":
        Return TOKEN_OR
    End If

    If word is equal to "not":
        Return TOKEN_NOT
    End If

    If word is equal to "in":
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If

    If word is equal to "for":
        Return TOKEN_FOR
    End If

    If word is equal to "true":
        Return TOKEN_TRUE
    End If

    If word is equal to "false":
        Return TOKEN_FALSE
    End If

    If word is equal to "nil":
        Return TOKEN_NIL
    End If

    If word is equal to "quote":
        Return TOKEN_QUOTE
    End If

    If word is equal to "unquote":
        Return TOKEN_UNQUOTE
    End If

    If word is equal to "unquote_splicing":
        Return TOKEN_UNQUOTE_SPLICING
    End If

    If word is equal to "import":
        Return TOKEN_IMPORT
    End If

    If word is equal to "alias":
        Return TOKEN_ALIAS
    End If

    If word is equal to "require":
        Return TOKEN_REQUIRE
    End If

    If word is equal to "use":
        Return TOKEN_USE
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a keyword
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE ATTRIBUTE LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Module attributes `@name` are macro markers for compile-time
information (e.g. @doc, @spec). The lexer keeps the leading @ in the
lexeme so the parser can recognize attributes positionally rather
than maintaining a separate atom-prefixed-with-@ representation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos, advances past the @ sigil, consumes
is_identifier_char characters, emits TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE with substring
from start_pos (including the @).
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_attribute" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position
    Call advance with lexer  Note: Skip @

    Note: Attribute name
    While is_identifier_char with lexer.current_char:
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    Let lexeme be substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE, lexeme
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SIGIL LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sigils `~X<...>` (or any matching delimiter pair) wrap arbitrary
content with custom delimiters and an optional modifier suffix. The
lexer consumes the whole construct as one TOKEN_SIGIL because the
content is opaque - the sigil-specific interpretation (regex, word
list, charlist, etc.) happens later in the pipeline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos, advances past `~`, reads sigil_type
(single character: s, r, w, c, etc.), advances. Reads delimiter,
computes closing_delimiter via get_closing_delimiter, advances past
the opening delimiter. Inner loop consumes characters until the
closing delimiter or EOF; backslash-escapes consume the backslash
plus next character without interpretation so escape sequences
survive verbatim into the lexeme. Advances past the closing
delimiter when present. Then consumes a trailing modifier run of
is_alpha characters (for regex flags like i, u, g, m). Emits
TOKEN_SIGIL with the substring from start_pos.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_sigil" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let start_pos be lexer.position
    Call advance with lexer  Note: Skip ~

    Note: Sigil type (s, r, w, c, etc.)
    Let sigil_type be lexer.current_char
    Call advance with lexer

    Note: Delimiter
    Let delimiter be lexer.current_char
    Let closing_delimiter be get_closing_delimiter with delimiter
    Call advance with lexer

    Note: Content
    While lexer.current_char is not equal to closing_delimiter and lexer.current_char is not equal to "":
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "\\":
            Call advance with lexer
        End If
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    If lexer.current_char is equal to closing_delimiter:
        Call advance with lexer
    End If

    Note: Modifiers (optional - for regex, etc.)
    While is_alpha with lexer.current_char:
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    Let lexeme be substring of lexer.source from start_pos to lexer.position
    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_SIGIL, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Elixir sigils accept several delimiter pairs - (), [], {}, <> - plus
symmetric pairs / and | where the same character serves as both
opener and closer. This helper centralizes the mapping so lex_sigil
doesn't carry a switch internally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the matching closer for "(" -> ")", "[" -> "]", "{" -> "}",
"<" -> ">". For "/" and "|" returns the same character. Falls
through to returning opening unchanged for any other character so the
sigil scanner can still close on a single-char delimiter.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_closing_delimiter" that takes opening as String returns String:
    If opening is equal to "(":
        Return ")"
    End If

    If opening is equal to "[":
        Return "]"
    End If

    If opening is equal to "{":
        Return "}"
    End If

    If opening is equal to "<":
        Return ">"
    End If

    If opening is equal to "/":
        Return "/"
    End If

    If opening is equal to "|":
        Return "|"
    End If

    Note: Default to same delimiter
    Return opening
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OPERATOR LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Operator recognition is longest-match: any three-character operator
must be tested before its two-character prefix, and two-character
forms before single-character forms, otherwise `===` would tokenize
as `==` followed by `=`. The two-look-ahead char and next2 are
fetched up front so each branch can decide based on the full
candidate length.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures char (current), next (peek 1), next2 (peek 2). Tests in
order:
- 3-char: `===` -> TOKEN_EQUAL_EQUAL_EQUAL, `!==` ->
  TOKEN_BANG_EQUAL_EQUAL, `...` -> TOKEN_TRIPLE_DOT (each advances 3).
- 2-char: `|>`, `->`, `=>`, `<>`, `++`, `--`, `<-`, `::`, `..`, `//`,
  `**`, `==`, `!=`, `<=`, `>=`, `<<`, `>>`, `&&`, `||` (each advances
  2 with the appropriate TOKEN_ constant).
- 1-char: `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`, `<`, `>`, `&`, `^`, `~`, `\`, `!`,
  `=` (each advances 1 with the appropriate single TOKEN_ constant).
Each branch emits via add_token with the operator's exact lexeme.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_operators" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let char be lexer.current_char
    Let next be peek with lexer and 1
    Let next2 be peek with lexer and 2

    Note: Three-character operators
    If char is equal to "=" and next is equal to "=" and next2 is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQUAL_EQUAL_EQUAL, "==="
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "!" and next is equal to "=" and next2 is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_BANG_EQUAL_EQUAL, "!=="
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "." and next is equal to "." and next2 is equal to ".":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_TRIPLE_DOT, "..."
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    Note: Two-character operators
    If char is equal to "|" and next is equal to ">":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_PIPE, "|>"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "-" and next is equal to ">":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW, "->"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "=" and next is equal to ">":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW, "=>"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "<" and next is equal to ">":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_CONCAT, "<>"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "+" and next is equal to "+":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS_PLUS, "++"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "-" and next is equal to "-":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS_MINUS, "--"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "<" and next is equal to "-":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LEFT_ARROW, "<-"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ":" and next is equal to ":":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, "::"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "." and next is equal to ".":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_DOT, ".."
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "/" and next is equal to "/":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_SLASH, "//"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "*" and next is equal to "*":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_STAR, "**"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "=" and next is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQUAL_EQUAL, "=="
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "!" and next is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_BANG_EQUAL, "!="
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "<" and next is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, "<="
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ">" and next is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, ">="
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "<" and next is equal to "<":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBIN, "<<"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ">" and next is equal to ">":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBIN, ">>"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "&" and next is equal to "&":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_AMPERSAND, "&&"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "|" and next is equal to "|":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_PIPE, "||"
        Call advance with lexer
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    Note: Single-character operators
    If char is equal to "+":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS, "+"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "-":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS, "-"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "*":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR, "*"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "/":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH, "/"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "%":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT, "%"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "<":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LESS, "<"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ">":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_GREATER, ">"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "&":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_AMPERSAND, "&"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "^":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_CARET, "^"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "~":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_TILDE, "~"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "\\":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_BACKSLASH, "\\"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "!":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_BANG, "!"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "=":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_ASSIGN, "="
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DELIMITER LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bracket, separator, and dot characters are all single-byte tokens
that the main loop has already pre-filtered via a delimiter test, so
this helper is a flat switch over the ten possibilities. Keeping
them separate from operators avoids ambiguous cases like `.` vs
`..`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single-char switch over current_char:
"(" -> TOKEN_LPAREN, ")" -> TOKEN_RPAREN, "[" -> TOKEN_LBRACKET,
"]" -> TOKEN_RBRACKET, "{" -> TOKEN_LBRACE, "}" -> TOKEN_RBRACE,
"." -> TOKEN_DOT, "," -> TOKEN_COMMA, ";" -> TOKEN_SEMICOLON,
"?" -> TOKEN_QUESTION.
Each branch emits via add_token and advances once.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_delimiters" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    Let char be lexer.current_char

    If char is equal to "(":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LPAREN, "("
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ")":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_RPAREN, ")"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "[":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACKET, "["
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "]":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACKET, "]"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "{":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACE, "{"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "}":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACE, "}"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ".":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT, "."
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ",":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_COMMA, ","
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to ";":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_SEMICOLON, ";"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If

    If char is equal to "?":
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_QUESTION, "?"
        Call advance with lexer
        Return
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN LEXER LOOP
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Main dispatch loop. Tests for each token shape in a deliberate order:
whitespace, newline, comment first (so trivia is consumed); then
numbers, strings, charlists, atoms, attributes, sigils,
identifiers/keywords (all "content" tokens); then operators and
delimiters (the punctuation set). Atoms are detected by `:` not
followed by whitespace, so `key: value` map syntax (where the colon
follows an identifier) doesn't trigger atom lexing. Sigils require
both `~` and an alpha character so subtraction operators starting
with `~` are not mis-tokenized.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops while current_char is not "" (not EOF). For each iteration tests
predicates and dispatches to the matching specialized lexer
(skip_whitespace, handle_newline, skip_comment, lex_number,
lex_string, lex_atom, lex_attribute, lex_sigil, lex_identifier,
lex_operators, lex_delimiters). Falls through to emitting
TOKEN_ERROR with the unknown character and advancing one step so the
lexer never loops infinitely on unexpected input. After the main loop
exits, appends a TOKEN_EOF sentinel so the parser can detect
end-of-stream by token type rather than list length.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex" that takes lexer as ElixirLexer returns Nothing:
    While lexer.current_char is not equal to "":
        Note: Skip whitespace
        If is_whitespace with lexer.current_char:
            Call skip_whitespace with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Handle newlines
        If is_newline with lexer.current_char:
            Call handle_newline with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Skip comments
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "#":
            Call skip_comment with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Numbers
        If is_digit with lexer.current_char:
            Call lex_number with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Strings
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "\"":
            Call lex_string with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Charlists
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "'":
            Call lex_string with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Atoms
        If lexer.current_char is equal to ":" and not is_whitespace with peek with lexer and 1:
            Call lex_atom with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Module attributes
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "@":
            Call lex_attribute with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Sigils
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "~" and is_alpha with peek with lexer and 1:
            Call lex_sigil with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Identifiers and keywords
        If is_identifier_start with lexer.current_char:
            Call lex_identifier with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Operators (multi-character checked first)
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "|" or lexer.current_char is equal to "-" or lexer.current_char is equal to "=" or lexer.current_char is equal to "<" or lexer.current_char is equal to ">" or lexer.current_char is equal to "+" or lexer.current_char is equal to "*" or lexer.current_char is equal to "/" or lexer.current_char is equal to "&" or lexer.current_char is equal to "^" or lexer.current_char is equal to "~" or lexer.current_char is equal to "\\" or lexer.current_char is equal to "!" or lexer.current_char is equal to "%":
            Call lex_operators with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Delimiters
        If lexer.current_char is equal to "(" or lexer.current_char is equal to ")" or lexer.current_char is equal to "[" or lexer.current_char is equal to "]" or lexer.current_char is equal to "{" or lexer.current_char is equal to "}" or lexer.current_char is equal to "." or lexer.current_char is equal to "," or lexer.current_char is equal to ";" or lexer.current_char is equal to "?":
            Call lex_delimiters with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Unknown character
        Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, lexer.current_char
        Call advance with lexer
    End While

    Note: Add EOF token
    Call add_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF, ""
End Process
